Code of Conduct


Our Pledge

To create an open and welcoming environment, we as contributors pledge to make participating in our project a harassment-free zone and a safe place for everyone to express themselves.

Our Standards

Appropriate behaviours:

Using welcoming and inclusive language
Being respectful of differing viewpoints and experiences
Gracefully accepting constructive criticism
Focusing on what is best for the community

Inappropriate behaviours:

Trolling, insulting/derogatory comments, and personal attacks
Public or private harassment
Publishing others' private information, or anything private without explicit permission
Other conduct which could reasonably be considered inappropriate in a professional setting

Our Responsibilities

Project maintainers are responsible for clarifying the standards of acceptable behaviour and are expected to take appropriate and fair corrective action in response to any instances of unacceptable behaviour.
We are responsible for maintaining the project goals
We are responsible for maintaining communication with project members
We are responsible for removing, editing, or rejecting comments, commits, code, wiki edits, issues, and other contributions that are not aligned to this Code of Conduct or that are off topic of the project.

Scope

This Code of Conduct applies within classes, meetings and in public spaces, such as the GitHub shared space.

Enforcement

Any complaints should be brought up during meetings, they will be reviewed and investigated and will result in a response that is deemed necessary and appropriate to the circumstances.
If a member is late for a meeting they will bring coffee for the next meeting. 
If a member breachers the code of conduct, depending on the breach, reprimanding actions will be taken.
Instances of abusive, harassing, or otherwise unacceptable behaviour may be reported to the Module leader.
The project team is obligated to maintain confidentiality with regard to the reporter of an incident. 
